\chapter*{Abstract}
\label{cha:abstract}

Everyday human environments have a underlying structure and knowledge about this structure is used by humans to carry out tasks efficiently. In this thesis a robotics system is presented, which uses such commonsense knowledge to execute an active object search in unknown open indoor environments in an intelligent way. This system uses the concept of rooms and the connection between the room type of an area and the objects usually located in that area to make estimations about the object probability in not or only vaguely seen areas. A mapping system was developed, which creates a semantic map of the environment containing the room structure and information about seen objects and room types of areas of the environment, which is extracted from images using convolutional neural networks. Based on this map a probabilistic planner generates view poses for the robot to drive to, which minimize the expected search time. Test runs of the developed system showed a more intelligent behavior and an improved performance compared to a coverage-maximizing search system. The findings of this work can be used in similar tasks with the goal to create robotic systems being able to help humans with a wide variety of tasks.


%This work proves again the potential of intelligent robotic systems, which utilize commonsense knowledge to execute tasks in everyday human environments more efficiently.

